</div>
<h2>What Is an MDR (Manifestation Determination Review)?</h2>
<p>An MDR is a crucial meeting required by IDEA to determine if a student's misconduct is a "manifestation" of their disability. In other words, the team needs to figure out: </p>
<ol>
<li>Was the conduct caused by, or did it have a direct and substantial relationship to, the child's disability?</li>
<li>Was the conduct the direct result of the school's failure to implement the IEP?</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Key Aspects of the MDR:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>The Team:</strong> The MDR team includes you (the parent/guardian), relevant members of the IEP team (including the special education teacher, a school administrator, and potentially related service providers like a therapist or counselor), and you have the right to bring your own advocate or attorney.</li>
<li><strong>Reviewing the IEP:</strong> The team must thoroughly review the child's IEP and all relevant information, including teacher observations, assessments, and your input as a parent.</li>
<li><strong>Causation:</strong> The burden is often on the school to demonstrate that the behavior was *not* related to the disability. Don't let them off the hook easily!  Demand clear and convincing evidence.</li>
<li><strong>IEP Implementation:</strong> If the school failed to properly implement the IEP, and that failure led to the behavior, the behavior *must* be considered a manifestation of the disability. This is a huge protection for your child!</li>
<li><strong>Manifestation:</strong> If the behavior *is* determined to be a manifestation of the disability, the school *cannot* suspend your child for more than 10 days (cumulative or a pattern), unless a Change of Placement is agreed upon (see below). The IEP team must then conduct a Functional Behavioral Assessment (FBA) if one has not been done, and develop a Behavior Intervention Plan (BIP) to address the behavior.  If an FBA and BIP are already in place, they need to be reviewed and revised to be more effective.</li>
<li><strong>Not a Manifestation:</strong> If the behavior is *not* a manifestation of the disability, the school can discipline your child in the same way as a student without a disability, BUT they *must* continue to provide special education services during the suspension, to the extent determined by the IEP team.</li>
<li><strong>Documentation is Key:</strong> The MDR decision *must* be documented in writing. Obtain a copy immediately.  If you disagree with the outcome, you have the right to appeal.</li>
<li><strong>Parent Participation:</strong>  Your input is *critical* at the MDR.  Prepare thoroughly. Bring documentation, observations, and examples of how your child's disability impacts their behavior.  Don't be intimidated!</li>
</ul>
<h2>Change of Placement</h2>
<p>A Change of Placement occurs when a student is removed from their current educational setting for more than 10 consecutive school days, or when a series of removals constitute a pattern because they cumulate to more than 10 school days in a school year, because of factors such as: the length of each removal, the total amount of time the child is removed, and the proximity of the removals to one another.</p>
<p><strong>What You Need To Know:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Manifestation Applies:</strong> A Change of Placement *always* requires a Manifestation Determination Review (MDR).</li>
<li><strong>Agreement Required:</strong> A Change of Placement usually requires the agreement of the IEP team, *including you*. Don't be pressured into agreeing to a placement you don't think is appropriate for your child!</li>
<li><strong>Alternative Settings:</strong> Changes of Placement can include moving a student to a different classroom, a specialized behavior support program, or even a homebound setting.  Carefully evaluate any proposed alternative placement to ensure it meets your child's educational and behavioral needs.</li>
<li><strong>Special Circumstances:</strong> There are very limited circumstances where a school can unilaterally remove a student for more than 45 school days, regardless of manifestation: if the student brings a weapon to school, possesses illegal drugs, or inflicts serious bodily injury on another person.  Even in these cases, due process protections still apply.</li>
<li><strong>Challenging a Change of Placement:</strong> If you disagree with a proposed Change of Placement, you have the right to pursue due process.  This is a complex legal process, so seek expert legal advice.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Filing a Level 1 Grievance</h2>
<p>If you believe Laredo ISD has violated your child's rights (e.g., improper suspension, failure to conduct an MDR, violation of the IEP), you have the right to file a grievance. Laredo ISD likely has a specific grievance policy, which you should obtain immediately. This information should be on the Laredo ISD website. Typically, the first step is a Level 1 grievance, addressed to the principal or relevant administrator.</p>
<p><strong>Key Steps for Filing a Level 1 Grievance:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Obtain the Policy:</strong> Locate and carefully review Laredo ISD's official grievance policy.  This will outline the specific procedures, timelines, and requirements.</li>
<li><strong>Written Grievance:</strong>  Your grievance *must* be in writing. Keep a copy for your records.</li>
<li><strong>Specifics:</strong>  Be clear and specific about the issue you are grieving.  Include dates, times, names of individuals involved, and specific violations of policy or law.</li>
<li><strong>Supporting Documentation:</strong>  Attach any relevant documentation, such as IEPs, suspension notices, emails, and witness statements.</li>
<li><strong>Relief Sought:</strong>  Clearly state what you want the school to do to resolve the issue.  (e.g., rescind the suspension, conduct an MDR, implement the IEP correctly).</li>
<li><strong>Timelines:</strong>  Pay close attention to the deadlines for filing a grievance and for the school to respond.  Missed deadlines can be fatal to your case.</li>
<li><strong>Delivery:</strong>  Deliver the grievance to the appropriate administrator (usually the principal) via certified mail with return receipt requested, or hand-deliver it and obtain a signed receipt.  This ensures proof of delivery.</li>
<li><strong>Follow Up:</strong> If you do not receive a timely response, follow up with the administrator in writing.  Document all communication.</li>
</ul>
<h2>TEA State Complaint</h2>
<p>In addition to the local grievance process, you have the right to file a complaint with the Texas Education Agency (TEA) if you believe Laredo ISD has violated IDEA or other special education laws. There are strict timelines involved.</p>
<p><strong>Important Considerations:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>One Year:</strong> TEA complaints must generally be filed within one year of the alleged violation.</li>
<li><strong>Federal Requirements:</strong> The complaint must meet specific federal requirements, including: A statement that a public agency has violated a requirement of Part B of IDEA or its implementing regulations, and the facts on which the statement is based.</li>
<li><strong>TEA Investigation:</strong> TEA will investigate your complaint and issue a written decision.</li>
<li><strong>Corrective Action:</strong> If TEA finds that Laredo ISD has violated the law, they can order the district to take corrective action, such as providing compensatory services to your child or implementing new policies.</li>
<li><strong>TEA Website:</strong> Visit the TEA website for detailed information on how to file a complaint and the required forms.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Due Process</h2>
<p>Due process is a formal legal procedure available to parents of students with disabilities when they disagree with the school district about their child's identification, evaluation, educational placement, or the provision of a free appropriate public education (FAPE). It is a more serious and complex process than a grievance or TEA complaint.</p>
<p><strong>Key Aspects of Due Process:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Mediation:</strong> Before filing for due process, you are usually required to participate in mediation with the school district. This is an opportunity to try to resolve the dispute informally.</li>
<li><strong>Filing a Due Process Complaint:</strong> If mediation is unsuccessful, you can file a formal due process complaint with TEA.  The complaint must meet specific legal requirements.</li>
<li><strong>Impartial Hearing Officer:</strong> An impartial hearing officer will be appointed to hear your case.</li>
<li><strong>Evidence and Testimony:</strong> You and the school district will present evidence and testimony at the due process hearing.</li>
<li><strong>Legal Representation:</strong> Due process hearings are essentially legal trials.  It is *highly* recommended that you seek legal representation from an attorney specializing in special education law.</li>
<li><strong>Hearing Officer Decision:</strong> The hearing officer will issue a written decision, which is legally binding.</li>
<li><strong>Appeal:</strong> You have the right to appeal the hearing officer's decision to state or federal court.</li>
<li><strong>Stay Put:</strong> During the due process proceedings, your child generally has the right to "stay put" in their current educational placement, unless you and the school district agree otherwise.</li>
</ul>
<p class="urgent"><strong>Disclaimer: This guide is for informational purposes only and does not constitute legal advice. You should consult with an attorney specializing in special education law to discuss your specific situation. Time is critical; act now to protect your child's rights. Contact Disability Rights Texas or other disability advocacy organizations for assistance.</strong></p>























